[According to the Dutch press, citing Gert-Jan Oplaat, chairman of the Dutch Poultry Farmers' Union, the damage caused by the outbreak of bird flu in Hekendorp can reach up to 100 million Euros [USD 125 million]. He said that the whole poultry industry is at standstill since the publication of the transport ban on Sunday [16 Nov 2014] afternoon.

Each day, 2 to 2.5 million chicks are born which now cannot be transported to the rearing farms. "All slaughterhouses and poultry processing plants are still. That means that 8000 employees of the poultry slaughterhouses are inactivated," he said. According to him, the damage to the sector by Monday [17 Nov 2014] has already been 10 to 20 million Euros [USD 12.5-25 million]. He also fears bankruptcies if the European Commission closes the borders for longer than a few days. (See, in Dutch, at http://tinyurl.com/kr2krqw). - Mod.AS]

******
[2]
Date: Mon 17 Nov 2014
Source: Irish Mirror [summarised, edited]
http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/irish-news/health-news/irish-farmers-worried-bird-flu-4645226


UK experts said that while the virus is deadly in poultry, the risks to humans are relatively small.

Professor Wendy Barclay, a leading virologist of Imperial College London, said the strain is unlikely to be harmful to humans except for farmers in direct contact infected animals.

Prof Barclay said: "Avian flu viruses have been seen in poultry in mainland Europe; the one in Yorkshire is likely to be the same as that seen in Germany and the Netherlands. It's good at infecting poultry -- including chickens, turkeys and geese -- because it's highly pathogenic. It kills very quickly. An infected bird will not develop symptoms over a period of time. It will just drop dead, often without warning." She added: "Meat can't carry it. Viruses are inert unless inside a living host."

[Byline: Sharon McGowan]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Dr Vallat's and Prof Barclay's views that the UK virus strain is/may be similar to the German and Dutch HPAI H5N8 strain are plausible; at this point, the full serotyping of the H5 HPAI virus strain on the East Yorkshire duck farm is still pending/not published; final results and genotyping are expected soon.

According to The Telegraph (17 Nov 2014), the affected farm is run by a company which has 2.8 billion ducks in China and farms in Germany (full text at http://tinyurl.com/nqjs8nr).

The following information on HPAI H5N8 in turkeys in Ireland (1983) may be of interest (thanks to Sabine Zentis for drawing attention to this event):

M.S. McNulty, G.M. Allan, R.M. McCracken & P.J. McParland (1985). Isolation of a highly pathogenic influenza virus from Turkeys, Avian Pathology, 14:1, 173-176, DOI: 10.1080/03079458508436216.

"SUMMARY
An influenza virus was isolated from turkeys with an acute disease causing 30 percent mortality. The virus was subtyped as H5N8. The nomenclature A/turkey/Ireland/83 (H5 N8) is proposed for this isolate. The virus had an ICPI of 1.80 to 1.85 for 1-day-old chicks and an IVPI of 2.74 for 6-week-old chickens. Following oronasal inoculation of juvenile and adult turkeys, chickens and ducks with the isolate, 100 percent mortality occurred in turkeys and chickens. No clinical signs were observed in inoculated ducks, but all developed serum antibody titres against the virus."

The authors stated that the source of virus in the outbreak was: "unknown. However, an influenza virus (H5N?) was isolated from a large duck-rearing enterprise very close to the infected turkey farm. As some of these ducks are kept outdoors for part of the year, one possibility is that they were originally infected by migrating feral waterfowl and that infection subsequently spread to the turkeys." - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2963428,15318.]
